Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Paula Teresa Dean in court, in custody.  Attorney Mary Garvin Guimont in court for Paula Teresa Dean.  
Attorney Olivia Simmons in court for State of Wisconsin.

Matter set for competency hearing.  Defendant now agrees with the report.  The court finds the defendant not competent to proceed but likely to become competent within the statutory time period.  if provided with appropriate treatment, is likely to become competent within 12 months or within the maximum sentence specified for the most serious offense, whichever is less.  The court orders the proceedings suspended and committed the defendant to the Department of Health Services FORTHWITH for an indeterminate term not to exceed 12 months, or the maximum sentence specified for the most serious offense, whichever is less.  Case is adjourned to Br. 1. This case will be heard via Zoom. Zoom meeting information provided to parties.
